          "studentExplanation": "Journeys are not only about people. Goods also move through routes, stops, transfer points, ports, warehouses, and trade policies. An entrepôt, a caravanserai, a waystation, a free-trade zone, or a transshipment point is not usually the final destination. It is a place where goods pause, change hands, avoid or delay duties, move from one vehicle to another, or connect one economy to another. From the Silk Road to Hong Kong and Chicago, trade hubs show that the modern world is built on things being constantly in transit: not fully here, not fully there, but moving through systems.\n\nThe extra notes help define the vocabulary: an entrepot stores and redistributes goods, a free-trade zone changes the tax and customs rules, transshipment combines routes through a middle point, and ports such as Hong Kong, Istanbul, Chicago, Lothal, Tyre, or Malacca matter because goods often “arrive” several times before reaching a buyer. Use this to connect travel with support systems: what moves, where it pauses, how services or hubs make movement possible, and why arrival depends on many places that are not the destination.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand that trade depends on routes and stopovers as much as human travel does. At the section level, it completes Call of Duty-Free by showing that movement includes goods, capital, customs, storage, and policy. At the year-theme level, it connects to “Are We There Yet?” because modern economies depend on things that are always between origins and destinations.",
          "takeaway": "Goods rarely move in one simple jump; they depend on intermediate places that organize transit, storage, policy, and exchange",
