          "rawOfficialText": "Is it always better to know how long it’ll take you to get somewhere? If not, what are examples of times when it would be better not to know?",
          "links": [],
          "studentExplanation": "People often say they want certainty, but exact timing is not always comforting. A countdown can help when you need to plan a connection, deadline, or safety decision. But in emotional situations, knowing exactly how long you must wait can make every minute feel heavier. This entry asks whether information is useful because it is accurate, or because it helps people act and cope.\n\nThe helpful distinction is practical waiting versus emotional waiting. A countdown can help at an airport gate, train platform, hospital queue, or project deadline because it supports planning, but in grief, punishment, illness, or suspense, exact time can make the delay heavier by turning every minute into something to watch. Use this to return to the theme: what counts as arrival, when waiting or quitting becomes reasonable, how closure changes a story or decision, and why getting there often opens another question.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see that knowledge changes feelings, not just decisions. At the section level, it returns to one of the year’s biggest questions: does knowing where you are in a journey always help? At the year-theme level, it connects to waiting and prediction because progress information can reduce anxiety, increase stress, or do both at the same time.",
