          "sectionId": "concluding-questions",
          "title": "The End of History—or Just Another Delay?",
          "guidingSection": "Concluding Questions",
          "rawOfficialText": "World War I was “the War to End All Wars”; 1989 was, per Francis Fukuyama, “The End of History”. The first meant achieving global peace; the second trumpeted the triumph of liberal democracy. The world isn’t there yet, in either case, but is it getting closer? Should one or both of these be our goals in the first place?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "The Conversation / repost - The End of History explained",
              "url": "https://theconversation.com/the-end-of-history-francis-fukuyamas-controversial-idea-explained-193225"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "This entry compares two huge historical hopes: the hope that World War I would end major war, and the belief that liberal democracy had won the main ideological struggle after the Cold War. Neither claim means that history literally stopped. Instead, both imagine a final destination: a world beyond war, or a political system beyond serious rivals. The question is whether humanity should aim for such endpoints, or whether history is too unstable for final arrival.\n\nThe two examples work because they both imagine a final destination for conflict: World War I as a war that would end war, and Fukuyama’s argument as an ideological endpoint after the Cold War. The sources make this useful as a warning: people often call something “over” because they need closure, even when the next phase has already started. Use this to return to the theme: what counts as arrival, when waiting or quitting becomes reasonable, how closure changes a story or decision, and why getting there often opens another question.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand two famous claims about historical endings. At the section level, it moves from personal choices and waiting to global political hopes. At the year-theme level, it connects to endings and progress because it asks whether societies can ever say “we’re there” in peace, politics, or history.",
          "takeaway": "A political ending can be inspiring but partial and reversible",
