          "sectionId": "going-pains",
          "title": "Growing Up Has Different Names",
          "guidingSection": "Going Pains",
          "rawOfficialText": "The word “adolescent” comes from a Latin word meaning “to grow toward”. But “teenager” relies on a quirk of the English language—that the numbers 11 and 12 have their own unique words, while 13 through 19 are compound words that combine a single-digit number and a suffix meaning “ten” (four-teen, six-teen, and so on). How do other languages refer to adolescents and teenagers—and does your own first language differentiate between these two terms? What are their different connotations? Do cultures with languages that use a -ten suffix for the numbers 11 and 12 define the “teenage” years differently? For instance, in Spanish, the -ten suffix only comes into play at 16—diez (10) y seis (6); do children only become teenagers at 16 in Spanish-speaking countries?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Etymonline - adolescent",
              "url": "https://www.etymonline.com/word/adolescent"
            },
            {
              "label": "Etymonline - teenager",
              "url": "https://www.etymonline.com/word/teenager"
            },
            {
              "label": "Britannica - adolescence",
              "url": "https://www.britannica.com/science/adolescence"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "This raw entry is mostly linguistic, so the key content is inside the wording itself. “Adolescent” comes from a growth-oriented Latin root, while “teenager” depends on a number pattern. Students should see that a word can define a life stage differently even when it points to similar ages.\nThe Spanish example is especially useful because it shows that English -teen does not map perfectly onto other languages. Spanish has special words for 11-15 and dieci- forms beginning at 16, but Spanish-speaking cultures do not wait until 16 to recognize adolescence.\nThe flashcards should not just translate “teenager.” They should compare whether a language frames the stage as age, growth, youth, puberty, or social identity.",
          "studentExplanation": "The word adolescent points toward growth: it comes from a root meaning to grow or grow toward maturity. The word teenager works differently: it depends on the English number pattern from thirteen to nineteen. That means the two words overlap, but they do not carry the same feeling. Adolescent sounds developmental or scientific; teenager sounds more social and cultural. Other languages divide the age range differently, which reminds us that life stages are partly biological and partly shaped by language.\n\nMake language part of the evidence. “Adolescent” points toward growth and maturity, while “teenager” depends on English number words; other languages sort youth, puberty, and social age in different ways. That means the category is partly biological, partly linguistic, and partly cultural. Use this to connect biology, language, and culture: what transition is happening, when society recognizes it, how people perform or resist maturity, and why growing up rarely matches one clean age line.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students notice that words do not just label growing up; they shape how people imagine it. At the section level, it adds language and culture to the science of adolescence. At the year-theme level, it connects to thresholds because language is one way societies draw fuzzy borders between child, youth, and adult.",
          "takeaway": "Life stages are shaped by biology and language",
