          "sectionId": "going-pains",
          "title": "Rites, Rules, and the Moment You “Become” an Adult",
          "guidingSection": "Going Pains",
          "rawOfficialText": "Many cultures hold special ceremonies to celebrate the passage from the dependency of childhood to the responsibilities of adulthood. With your team, explore the following rites of passage and consider: what is the difference between a cultural rite, such as a quinceañera, and a secular one, like graduating from high school?\nSweet sixteens | Fiesta de Quinceañera | Vision quests | Guan Li | Seijin no Hi | Bar and Bat Mitzvahs | Walkabout | Khatam al-Quran | debuts | high school graduation | driver’s license | first paycheck | national service | voting | moving out",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Quinceañera visual",
              "url": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Quincea%C3%B1eras_001.jpg"
            },
            {
              "label": "Coming of Age Day visual",
              "url": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coming_of_Age_Day.jpg"
            },
            {
              "label": "Bar mitzvah visuals",
              "url": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Bar_mitzvah"
            },
            {
              "label": "Britannica - rite of passage",
              "url": "https://www.britannica.com/topic/rite-of-passage"
            },
            {
              "label": "Britannica - Arnold van Gennep",
              "url": "https://www.britannica.com/biography/Arnold-van-Gennep"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The Britannica/van Gennep framework should shape this entry: rites of passage are not random celebrations; they organize movement from one status to another through separation, transition/liminality, and incorporation. This links directly to the year theme and to liminal thresholds.\nThe raw list deliberately mixes traditional, religious, public, legal, and everyday rites. The slideshow should keep that variety instead of making every example look like a birthday party.\nThe three Wikimedia visual links matter because rites of passage are highly visual. Quinceañera, Seijin no Hi, and Bar/Bat Mitzvah examples will help students see how clothing, ceremony, public recognition, and family/community presence make transition visible.\nWalkabout needs especially careful handling. The slide should avoid treating it as a generic adventure or tourist myth; it should be framed respectfully as a concept often simplified or misrepresented in outside sources.",
          "studentExplanation": "Growing up is usually gradual, but many communities create special moments that say: now something has changed. Some rites of passage are cultural or religious, like a quinceañera, Seijin no Hi, or bar/bat mitzvah. Others are secular or legal, like graduation, voting, a driver’s license, national service, or moving out. The important point is that a rite turns a slow and messy transition into a visible social moment that other people recognize.\n\nThe extra sources help students ask what the ceremony is doing socially. A quinceanera, Seijin no Hi, bar or bat mitzvah, vision quest, graduation, driver’s license, or national service does not cause maturity by itself; it gives a community a visible moment when it agrees to treat a person differently. Use this to connect biology, language, and culture: what transition is happening, when society recognizes it, how people perform or resist maturity, and why growing up rarely matches one clean age line.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows that adulthood is not only biology; it is also marked by symbols, ceremonies, rights, and responsibilities. At the section level, it gives a social answer to the science of adolescence: rites of passage make change legible. At the year-theme level, rites of passage are literal threshold events between one status and another.",
          "takeaway": "Communities give visible shape to uncertain transitions",
