          "sectionId": "going-pains",
          "title": "“Adulting”: Acting Like a Grown-Up",
          "guidingSection": "Going Pains",
          "rawOfficialText": "Millennials—people born between about 1981 and 1995—gave us side parts, skinny jeans, and “adulting”. This term transformed adulthood into a verb, something you do (often with great effort) rather than something you simply are. Whether going to bed early, scheduling a dentist appointment, or buying a vacuum cleaner, describing your actions as “adulting” implies you are just role-playing as a grown-up. Consider with your team: is being an adult a specific feeling or just a collection of habits and responsibilities? When do you think you will feel like an adult?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Time - definition and discussion of “adulting”",
              "url": "https://time.com/4361866/adulting-definition-meaning/"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The Time article must be treated as core content because it explains the cultural logic of “adulting”: the speaker performs adult tasks while keeping ironic distance from being a “real adult.” The word is funny because it turns adulthood into an action rather than a settled identity.\nThis entry should connect to the app’s year theme through performance and thresholds. “Adulting” makes adulthood feel like a series of repeatable tasks: paying bills, scheduling appointments, sleeping responsibly, buying practical objects, and managing everyday life.\nThe entry is strongest when it does not mock young adults. It should show that adulting language reveals real uncertainty about when adulthood begins in contemporary life.",
          "studentExplanation": "Adulting turns adulthood into a verb: something you do, often awkwardly, instead of something you simply are. The Time link explains why the joke works: when people say they are “adulting,” they often mean they are doing grown-up tasks while still feeling a little distant from the identity of a “real adult.” Paying bills, making appointments, cooking, cleaning, buying practical things, or going to bed early can all feel like performances of adulthood before adulthood feels natural.\n\nThe useful detail is that “adulting” names a gap between task and identity. Paying bills, scheduling appointments, cooking, cleaning, or making practical purchases can make someone look adult from the outside while still feeling like rehearsal on the inside. Use this to connect biology, language, and culture: what transition is happening, when society recognizes it, how people perform or resist maturity, and why growing up rarely matches one clean age line.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand why adulthood can feel like a performance. At the section level, it modernizes Going Pains by showing how culture jokes about the gap between responsibility and identity. At the year-theme level, adulting is a liminal habit: a person is doing adult things while still asking whether they have really arrived.",
          "takeaway": "Adulthood may be performed before it feels real",
          "subjects": [
            "Sociology",
            "Psychology"
          ],
