          "sectionId": "home-and-wandering",
          "title": "Poems of Migration and In-Between Lives",
          "guidingSection": "Home and Wandering",
          "rawOfficialText": "Consider the following poems that speak to the immigrant experience. Are they expressing something universal, or are they too constrained by the specific experience of migrating to the United States? In what ways do they relate to the idea of thresholds and liminal spaces?\nEmma Lazarus | “The New Colossus” (1883)\nAdrienne Rich | “Prospective Immigrants Please Note” (1963)\nMarilyn Chin | “We Are Americans Now, We Live in the Tundra” (1987)\nAdrian Castro | “The Sound of One Immigrant Clapping” (2005)\nRichard Blanco | “Mother Country” (2019)",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Emma Lazarus - “The New Colossus”",
              "url": "https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/46550/the-new-colossus"
            },
            {
              "label": "Adrienne Rich - “Prospective Immigrants Please Note”",
              "url": "https://www.getty.edu/education/teachers/classroom_resources/curricula/dorothea_lange/downloads/lange_lesson11_adriennerich.rtf"
            },
            {
              "label": "Marilyn Chin - “We Are Americans Now, We Live in the Tundra”",
              "url": "https://poets.org/poem/we-are-americans-now-we-live-tundra"
            },
            {
              "label": "Adrian Castro - “The Sound of One Immigrant Clapping”",
              "url": "https://poets.org/poem/sound-one-immigrant-clapping"
            },
            {
              "label": "Richard Blanco - “Mother Country”",
              "url": "https://poets.org/poem/mother-country"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "These poem links should not be treated as decoration; each gives a different angle on migration. “The New Colossus” turns immigration into a symbol of welcome attached to the Statue of Liberty. Adrienne Rich’s poem is almost a threshold manual: crossing and not crossing both change the person. Marilyn Chin’s poem complicates becoming American through ancestry, environment, irony, and identity.\nAdrian Castro’s poem works through sound, music, language, and Caribbean memory; it asks how an immigrant voice survives displacement. Richard Blanco’s “Mother Country” moves through family memory and exile, making migration intergenerational rather than only personal. The slideshow should therefore compare emotional functions: welcome, warning, transformation, language, and inherited memory.",
          "studentExplanation": "These poems show migration from the inside: hope, warning, memory, ancestry, language, loss, and the strange feeling of being between homes. The links matter because each poem gives a different version of the threshold. Lazarus imagines welcome, Rich warns that crossing changes you, Chin explores becoming American while carrying older histories, Castro focuses on voice and language, and Blanco turns exile into family memory. Together they show that migration is not only movement; it is a transformation of identity.\n\nRead the poems as different emotional geographies. Lazarus imagines welcome, Rich warns that every choice has risk, Chin uses animals and tundra to show displacement, Castro turns identity into rhythm, and Blanco shows how memory travels with ordinary objects from the old home. Use this to track movement beyond simple maps: what is guiding the traveler, where the threshold or border sits, how tools, animals, memory, or law shape arrival, and why being near home is not always the same as belonging.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see how poetry can hold complicated migration feelings in a small space. At the section level, it gives Home and Wandering an emotional and literary voice after the policy and navigation entries. At the year-theme level, it connects to thresholds because migrants may cross borders physically while still living between languages, memories, and homes.",
          "takeaway": "Migration poetry turns movement, exile, welcome, and belonging into felt human experience.",
