          "studentExplanation": "Products often begin as rough drafts. Before a company builds something at full scale, it can test early versions to see what works, what fails, and what users actually need. A prototype may look unfinished, but that is its value: it lets people learn before they spend too much time, money, or trust on the final version.\n\nThe extra notes define the ladder of prototyping: sketches, storyboards, paper prototypes, wireframes, mockups, proof of concept, minimum viable product, and user testing are not synonyms. Each answers a different question: can we imagine it, can people understand it, can it work, and is it worth building? Use this to judge readiness: what kind of model is being shown, how close it is to the final thing, where humans or assumptions are hidden, and why a prototype can both teach and mislead.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows that a prototype is not a failed product but a learning version. At the section level, it opens Monkey See, Monkey Prototype by showing that invention usually moves through trial versions. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress because getting “there” often requires unfinished forms first.",
