          "sectionId": "monkey-see-monkey-prototype",
          "title": "The Mechanical Turk and the Ethics of Fake Intelligence",
          "guidingSection": "Monkey See, Monkey Prototype",
          "rawOfficialText": "In 1770, a Hungarian engineer announced a startling invention: a machine capable of playing chess. This “Mechanical Turk” toured the world, impressing everyone from Benjamin Franklin to Edgar Allan Poe. There was just one problem: it was not an early example of AI, but a hoax, operated by a chess master hidden within. Companies today may still take a similar approach-known as “Wizard of Oz” testing-to test user response before production. Discuss with your team: is it okay to mislead users during product testing in order to make the finished versions of those products better?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Mechanical Turk image / history",
              "url": "https://slate.com/human-interest/2015/08/the-turk-a-chess-playing-robot-was-a-hoax-that-started-an-early-conversation-about-ai.html"
            },
            {
              "label": "Wizard of Oz testing explanation",
              "url": "https://www.thisisservicedesigndoing.com/methods/wizard-of-oz-approaches"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "The Mechanical Turk looked like a machine that could play chess, but a hidden human actually controlled the moves. Modern Wizard of Oz testing is not exactly the same as a hoax: designers sometimes simulate an unfinished system so they can learn how users respond before building the full product. The ethical problem is transparency. A simulation can help design, but it can also mislead people if they believe the system is more real or more capable than it is.\n\nThe Mechanical Turk is the old version of a modern tech problem: the audience thinks it is seeing a machine, but a human operator supplies the intelligence. Wizard-of-Oz testing can be legitimate if disclosed inside research, but deceptive if it sells readiness that does not exist. Use this to judge readiness: what kind of model is being shown, how close it is to the final thing, where humans or assumptions are hidden, and why a prototype can both teach and mislead.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students separate testing, simulation, and deception. At the section level, it shows that some prototypes work by hiding what is incomplete. At the year-theme level, it connects to thresholds because a product can cross from useful simulation into unfair deception.",
          "takeaway": "Simulated systems can help design, but hidden help should not create false trust.",
          "subjects": [
            "History"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Visible vs Real",
            "Incompletion That Stays Active",
            "Performed Progress",
            "Infrastructure Shapes Behavior"
          ],
