          "sectionId": "monkey-see-monkey-prototype",
          "title": "Rigged Demos and the Performance of Readiness",
          "guidingSection": "Monkey See, Monkey Prototype",
          "rawOfficialText": "Elon Musk once unveiled a prototype humanoid robot that turned out to be a dancer in a costume. His more recent demonstrations are closer-but still not quite there. Read about some other examples of companies faking demonstrations of their not-quite-ready products, then discuss with your team: should companies be required to tell people when demos are slightly or entirely rigged?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Tesla Bot costume reveal",
              "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/technology/video/2021/aug/20/elon-musk-plan-tesla-bot-man-dancing-bodysuit-video"
            },
            {
              "label": "Later Optimus teleoperation / autonomy concerns",
              "url": "https://techcrunch.com/2024/10/14/tesla-optimus-bots-were-controlled-by-humans-during-the-we-robot-event/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Staged technology demo examples",
              "url": "https://sea.mashable.com/tech/34699/fake-tech-demos-a-brief-history"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "A demo can make a product look closer to ready than it really is. The Tesla Bot costume reveal is an extreme example: the audience saw a performance standing in for a future robot. Later robot demonstrations looked more advanced, but still raised questions about how much was autonomous and how much depended on control, staging, or careful conditions. This entry is about the performance of readiness: companies can show a future product in ways that inspire belief before the product is fully real.\n\nUse Tesla Bot and other staged demos to separate demonstration from capability. A demo can prove vision, attract funding, or teach designers, but it can also make audiences believe a system is autonomous, safe, or close to market when it is still largely performance. Use this to judge readiness: what kind of model is being shown, how close it is to the final thing, where humans or assumptions are hidden, and why a prototype can both teach and mislead.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand why demos can persuade even when they are not full proof. At the section level, it shows a darker side of prototyping, where showing the future becomes performance. At the year-theme level, it connects to prediction because public demos shape what people believe is about to arrive.",
          "takeaway": "Trustworthy demos should show what is real, what is staged, and what is still unfinished.",
          "subjects": [
            "Computer Science / Technology",
            "Economics & Trade"
          ],
