          "sectionId": "more-to-do-than-can-ever-be-listed",
          "title": "The Zeigarnik Effect and the Done List",
          "guidingSection": "More To Do Than Can Ever Be Listed",
          "rawOfficialText": "It is easier to remember things we did not finish than those we did. That is why a song that got interrupted might nag at you until you hear the end of it, ooh na na - or why you might be unable to keep an overdue assignment out of your head even when you are taking a break. Psychologists term this the Zeigarnik Effect. Discuss with your team: how can we use the Zeigarnik Effect to our advantage in tasks like preparing for the World Scholar’s Cup? Would we be healthier if we spent more time remembering the things we got done - keeping a done list - than the things we did not?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Zeigarnik Effect - Psychology Today",
              "url": "https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/zeigarnik-effect"
            },
            {
              "label": "Done list - Oliver Burkeman",
              "url": "https://www.oliverburkeman.com/donelist"
            },
            {
              "label": "Supplementary Zeigarnik explanation - Psych Central",
              "url": "https://psychcentral.com/health/zeigarnik-effect"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "The Zeigarnik Effect explains why unfinished tasks can keep returning to your mind. An incomplete assignment, an interrupted song, or a half-finished WSC study plan can feel mentally open, so your brain keeps checking it. This can be useful because it pushes you back toward unfinished work, but it can also become stressful when too many open tasks compete for attention. The Psychology Today link adds a very practical idea: you do not always have to finish the task immediately to calm the mind; making a specific plan can help close the mental loop. The done-list link then flips the focus. Instead of only tracking what remains unfinished, a done list records what has already been completed, which can fight the feeling that you are always behind.\n\nThe source notes sharpen the mechanism: unfinished tasks stay mentally active because the mind keeps checking the open loop. A done list works differently from a to-do list because it records movement already made, which can reduce the feeling of productivity debt and help students see progress instead of only lack. Use this to distinguish planning from completion: what the list records, where attention gets stuck, how a method changes behavior, and why unfinished work keeps returning to the mind.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this explains why incompletion feels psychologically powerful. At the section level, it shows that planning is not only about external lists, but also about memory, anxiety, and attention. At the year-theme level, it connects to delay and progress because unfinished journeys can motivate us, exhaust us, or become easier to handle when we give them structure.",
          "takeaway": "Unfinished work needs structure, not obsession",
          "subjects": [
            "Psychology"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Incompletion That Stays Active",
            "Managing Uncertainty",
            "Delayed Arrival",
            "Infrastructure Shapes Behavior"
          ],
