          "sectionId": "next-year-in-futurism",
          "title": "Tesla’s Tower and the Meaning of “Soon”",
          "guidingSection": "Next Year in Futurism",
          "rawOfficialText": "“It will soon be possible to transmit wireless messages all over the world so simply that any individual can own and operate his own apparatus,” the inventor Nikola Tesla told the New York Times in 1904. Whether it was an accurate prediction of the smartphone depends on what you think the meaning of “soon” is. For Tesla, soon meant, “I’m building it right now; I just need more funding.” Read more about his Wardenclyffe Tower and the reasons it failed, then discuss with your team: what if it had succeeded?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Tesla Science Center - The Tower",
              "url": "https://teslasciencecenter.org/history/tower/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Tesla Science Center - History of Wardenclyffe",
              "url": "https://teslasciencecenter.org/staging/history/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Tesla Science Center - The Journey",
              "url": "https://teslasciencecenter.org/history/journey/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Tesla’s 1904 prediction of personal wireless communication sounds astonishingly close to the smartphone, but Wardenclyffe shows why being visionary is not the same as arriving. Tesla imagined global wireless communication and power, and the tower was meant to be a prototype for a worldwide system. The project failed because of funding, timing, technical ambition, and lack of institutional support. Students should see Tesla as both impressively forward-looking and overconfident about how soon a world-scale system could be built.\n\nWardenclyffe makes “soon” historically concrete: Tesla imagined wireless communication and power before infrastructure, funding, regulation, and physics could make the dream practical. The tower failed not only as an invention but as a promise that depended on a whole system arriving with it. Use this to audit promises: what future is being predicted, when people expected it, how technical or social limits delayed it, and why “soon” can be a feeling rather than a calendar date.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows that a prediction can point in the right direction while still failing in its actual form. At the section level, it develops futurism as a problem of timing, funding, infrastructure, and credibility. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress and planning because the future belongs not only to big ideas, but to ideas that can survive implementation.",
          "takeaway": "A prediction can be visionary and still fail as a practical route",
