          "sectionId": "next-year-in-futurism",
          "title": "Yesterday’s Tomorrow",
          "guidingSection": "Next Year in Futurism",
          "rawOfficialText": "Read about some of the futuristic technologies predicted in the past, then watch this video that shows how those predictions evolved across the 20th century. Some of them seem fantastical—an Olympics on the moon in the year 2020?—but others may already be within our reach, or just slightly beyond (where they may or may not get stuck). With your team, consider: what can we learn about the past from where people thought we were going? Are any of the things that people predicted about the 21st century things you might now predict for the 22nd?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Rare Historical Photos - retro future predictions",
              "url": "https://rarehistoricalphotos.com/retro-future-predictions/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Old visions of the future are not just funny mistakes. They show what past societies thought progress should look like: faster travel, easier homes, space colonies, automated work, new foods, and dazzling machines. Some predictions seem absurd now, but others look like early versions of technologies that arrived differently. Students should read retrofuturism as a mirror: every future picture also reveals the past that imagined it.\n\nRetrofuturism should be explained as looking at old futures from the present. Moon Olympics, automatic homes, nuclear cars, food pills, and streamlined cities reveal what past societies feared, desired, or misunderstood, so failed predictions still teach history. Use this to audit promises: what future is being predicted, when people expected it, how technical or social limits delayed it, and why “soon” can be a feeling rather than a calendar date.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this teaches students to compare accuracy with cultural meaning. At the section level, it gives futurism historical depth. At the year-theme level, it connects to prediction because “tomorrow” always carries the values, fears, and design tastes of “yesterday.”",
          "takeaway": "Every imagined tomorrow also reveals the culture that imagined it",
