          "sectionId": "next-year-in-futurism",
          "title": "Quantum Supremacy and the Fear of Q-Day",
          "guidingSection": "Next Year in Futurism",
          "rawOfficialText": "Who wouldn’t want quantum supremacy? In 2019, Google made a splashy headline: they’d achieved it! Others soon claimed they had too. But researchers admit quantum computers still have no practical purpose, even as cryptographers worry that they could someday be used to hack even the most encrypted passwords. Read more about this much-dreaded Q-Day, then discuss with your team: should we be developing technologies that have unclear practical advantages but clear downsides?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Popular Mechanics - Google quantum supremacy",
              "url": "https://www.popularmechanics.com/science/energy/a29563154/google-achieves-quantum-supremacy/"
            },
            {
              "label": "CNBC - quantum computing applications and limits",
              "url": "https://www.cnbc.com/2025/06/27/quantum-computing-applications-how-it-works.html"
            },
            {
              "label": "WIRED - Q-Day and encryption risk",
              "url": "https://www.wired.com/story/q-day-apocalypse-quantum-computers-encryption/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Quantum computing is a good example of a technology that can be impressive before it is broadly useful. “Quantum supremacy” means a quantum system performed a specific task beyond what a classical computer could easily do, but that does not mean quantum computers are ready for everyday work. At the same time, cybersecurity experts worry about Q-Day: the moment when a powerful enough quantum computer could break major encryption systems. The same technology can therefore look like a scientific triumph and a security threat before most people can use it at all.\n\nAdd the distinction between milestone and usefulness: quantum supremacy proves a quantum machine can outperform classical machines on a specific task, but it does not mean everyday quantum laptops have arrived. Q-Day is a security fear about cryptography, planning, and migration before the threat is practical. Use this to audit promises: what future is being predicted, when people expected it, how technical or social limits delayed it, and why “soon” can be a feeling rather than a calendar date.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students separate breakthrough headlines from practical usefulness. At the section level, it makes futurism darker by showing that risk can arrive before benefit. At the year-theme level, it connects to bright/dark futures and prediction because the future may be powerful before it is safe.",
          "takeaway": "Society must prepare for risks before everyday benefits are obvious",
          "subjects": [
            "Computer Science / Technology",
            "Sciences"
          ],
