          "title": "What Would AGI Change?",
          "guidingSection": "Next Year in Futurism",
          "rawOfficialText": "Deep learning-driven neural networks excel at competing high school English assignments, but it’s not clear that they’re getting anywhere close to artificial general intelligence (AGI)—that is, to an AI that mirrors the ability of humans to learn, understand, and apply knowledge across unlimited contexts. Discuss with your team: should we want to get there? How will our lives change if and when we do?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "BBC Science Focus - AI bubble and AGI limits",
              "url": "https://www.sciencefocus.com/future-technology/hidden-forces-ai-bubble"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Artificial general intelligence, or AGI, would be much broader than today’s task-specific AI. Current systems can write, summarize, code, classify, or generate media impressively, but they still struggle with reliability, grounding, outliers, and true understanding. The Science Focus article is useful because it challenges the assumption that simply scaling bigger models will automatically reach AGI. Students should understand the key debate: the question is not only whether AGI is possible, but whether society should race toward something that could transform work, knowledge, power, and human self-understanding.\n\nUse narrow AI versus AGI as the first distinction. Current systems can be impressive and brittle at once: they generate fluent work, hallucinate, depend on data and evaluation, and struggle with rare cases. The real question is what human institutions would change if a general system became reliable. Use this to audit promises: what future is being predicted, when people expected it, how technical or social limits delayed it, and why “soon” can be a feeling rather than a calendar date.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students distinguish current AI from the larger AGI idea. At the section level, it raises the stakes of futurism by asking what kind of intelligence society is trying to build. At the year-theme level, it connects to bright/dark futures because AGI can be imagined as salvation, disruption, or both.",
          "takeaway": "The real destination is not only technical but civilizational",
