          "sectionId": "progress-not-regress",
          "title": "Play to Wait",
          "guidingSection": "Progress, Not Regress",
          "rawOfficialText": "In 1994, the developers of Namco's Ridge Racer added an Easter egg to their loading screens - a version of the studio's classic Galaxian game. Google Chrome does something similar: its Dinosaur Game appears when your device goes offline temporarily. In the real world, some restaurants now encourage diners to play games on table-mounted payment terminals (for a fee) while waiting for their food. Discuss with your team: should more processes come with these kinds of auxiliary games to help people pass the time?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Google blog - Chrome Dinosaur Game",
              "url": "https://blog.google/products-and-platforms/products/chrome/chrome-dino/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Wired - Namco loading-screen minigame patent",
              "url": "https://www.wired.com/story/namco-patent-ends-allowing-loading-screen-minigames"
            },
            {
              "label": "NBC Chicago - restaurant table games fee",
              "url": "https://www.nbcchicago.com/investigations/consumer/restaurant-tablet-games-charges/3148266/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Auxiliary games turn waiting into a small side activity. Ridge Racer famously let players play Galaxian during loading, Chrome's Dino game turns internet failure into a mini runner, and some restaurants now offer games on table terminals while customers wait. These examples show a shift from showing progress to filling time. The user is not necessarily closer to the end, but the wait becomes more active, playful, or profitable.\n\nLoading games show that waiting can be converted into play. Ridge Racer, Chrome Dino, and restaurant-table games all fill delay differently: one entertains during technical limits, one turns disconnection into a mini-game, and one can become a hidden paid distraction. Use this to separate real progress from visible progress: what is actually changing, what the user can see, how the indicator changes behavior, and when reassurance becomes manipulation.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand that waiting can be transformed into entertainment. At the section level, it expands progress design beyond bars and buttons into play. At the year-theme level, it connects to journeys because the middle of a route can become valuable, enjoyable, or exploitative in its own right.",
          "takeaway": "Entertainment can help waiting, but it can also monetize or exploit boredom",
          "subjects": [
            "Psychology"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Movement Without Arrival",
            "Delayed Arrival",
            "Performed Progress",
            "Visible vs Real"
          ],
          "examples": [
            "Ridge Racer loading game",
            "Chrome Dinosaur Game",
            "Restaurant table games"
          ],
          "debateRelevance": "Useful when debating whether boredom should be filled with entertainment or whether every idle moment is being monetized.",
          "counterargument": "Small waiting games can be harmless or delightful when they are optional and not used to hide fees.",
