          "sectionId": "progress-not-regress",
          "title": "Is the World on Its Way to a Better or Worse Place?",
          "guidingSection": "Progress, Not Regress",
          "rawOfficialText": "The Second Law of Thermodynamics suggests that closed systems always grow more disordered over time. Left to themselves, things get messier: your room won't clean itself. Yet many people take for granted that the world as a whole should become better over time. 'The arc of the moral universe is long, but it bends toward justice,' said Martin Luther King, Jr., a quote that may have preceded and certainly outlived him. But it turns out that this idea that the world improves over time may be a relatively new one (alternate link). Discuss with your team: is the world growing better? Be sure to check out the artist Will Crawford's answer to this question in this 1909 painting. What would a painting with the same title look like today?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "The Atlantic - Progress is not natural / progress history context",
              "url": "https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/01/science-technology-vaccine-invention-history/672227/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Will Crawford - Surely the World Is Growing Better - Library of Congress/Wikimedia",
              "url": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Surely_the_world_is_growing_better_-_Will_Crawford._LCCN2011647517.jpg"
            },
            {
              "label": "Theodore Roosevelt Center - Will Crawford image record",
              "url": "https://www.theodorerooseveltcenter.org/digital-library/o288522/"
            },
            {
              "label": "MLK / moral arc quote context - White House archive",
              "url": "https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2011/10/21/arc-moral-universe-long-it-bends-toward-justice"
            },
            {
              "label": "Theodore Parker / MLK quote history context",
              "url": "https://bendingarc.com/the-arc"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "This entry contrasts two ideas of time. The Second Law of Thermodynamics gives a simple image of decline: left alone, systems tend toward disorder. But modern societies often imagine history as progress: more knowledge, more justice, better health, better rights, and a better future. That optimistic idea is not universal or timeless. Some cultures imagined history as cyclical, controlled by higher powers, or outside human influence. Will Crawford's 1909 cartoon adds a dark twist: if technology improves warfare, then 'the world is growing better' can become bitter irony.\n\nUse “Surely the World Is Growing Better” as a test of progress stories. A painting full of more advanced warfare can imply that technology improves capacity without improving morality, so students should ask whether progress means power, comfort, fairness, safety, or wisdom. Use this to separate real progress from visible progress: what is actually changing, what the user can see, how the indicator changes behavior, and when reassurance becomes manipulation.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students ask whether progress is natural, chosen, measured, or imagined. At the section level, it closes Progress, Not Regress by questioning the assumption that forward movement is always improvement. At the year-theme level, it connects to bright and dark futures because getting 'there' only matters if we know whether 'there' is better, worse, or simply more powerful.",
          "takeaway": "Whether human progress is real, automatic, fragile, or partly imagined",
          "subjects": [
            "Philosophy",
            "History"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Narrated Endings",
            "Managing Uncertainty",
            "Measuring Human Worth",
            "Visible vs Real"
          ],
