          "sectionId": "the-end-is-nearish",
          "title": "Lame Ducks and Fading Power",
          "guidingSection": "The End is Nearish",
          "rawOfficialText": "The United States has no caretaker governments (neither does Venezuela), but it does limit its presidents to two four-year terms in office. As their second term begins to run out, they inevitably find themselves losing power and influence. They are said to become “lame ducks” as the country turns its attention to younger, healthier ducks who might win the next election. Discuss with your team: to prevent lame ducks, would it be better to have no limits on how long a person can lead a country or organization? What would you advise someone wanting to hold onto power for as long as possible?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Twenty-Second Amendment - Cornell LII",
              "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/amendmentxxii"
            },
            {
              "label": "EBSCO - Lame duck politics",
              "url": "https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/political-science/lame-duck-politics"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The raw content gives the United States as the major example, so the Twenty-Second Amendment should be preserved as a useful added link. It explains the structural cause of many lame-duck moments in U.S. presidential politics: a president cannot be elected more than twice.\nThe entry is not only about the phrase “lame duck.” It is about the gap between legal authority and practical influence. A leader may still have the office, staff, and title, but allies, rivals, donors, media, and voters may already be oriented toward the next leader.\nThe debate should not become simply “term limits good or bad.” It should ask what societies gain and lose when endings are visible in advance: predictability, accountability, weakened influence, succession battles, or protection against permanent rule.",
          "studentExplanation": "A lame duck leader is still in office, but everyone knows the end is coming, so influence starts slipping before the official finish line. In the United States, the two-term presidential limit helps create this problem because a second-term president cannot run again. The real issue is a trade-off: term limits can protect a system from permanent leadership, but they can also make a leader weaker before the term is actually over.\n\nA lame duck has office without the same future leverage. The important “when” is before the term actually ends: allies, opponents, voters, and bureaucracies start reacting to the next leader, so power fades socially before it disappears legally. Use this to track how endings begin before they officially happen: what is ending, who notices it first, what signs make it feel near, and why people act differently in the near-end zone.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see that political endings can begin before the calendar says they have arrived. At the section level, it extends The End Is Nearish from temporary governments to fading authority. At the year-theme level, it connects to endings and prediction because knowing the finish line changes how everyone behaves before reaching it.",
          "takeaway": "Formal office and real influence can diverge",
          "subjects": [
            "Politics & Government / Global Politics"
          ],
