          "title": "If No One Knew Who Was Next",
          "guidingSection": "The End is Nearish",
          "rawOfficialText": "Queen Elizabeth I’s solution was to delay naming her successor. “I know the inconstancy of the people of England,” she is said to have told the Scottish ambassador, “How they ever mislike the present government and have their eyes fixed upon the person who is next to succeed.” Discuss with your team: would it be better if no one knew who the next leader would be until after the current leader left (or died)? Can you find an example of such a system?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Elizabeth I - Britannica",
              "url": "https://www.britannica.com/biography/Elizabeth-I"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The raw Elizabeth quotation matters because it identifies a psychological mechanism: subjects may “mislike” present government and look toward the next ruler before the current reign ends. This makes succession a mental transition before it is a legal one.\nElizabeth I’s delayed succession is a strong case for the section because it shows that uncertainty can be useful to someone in power. Not naming the future can preserve present loyalty, but it can also store up danger, factional competition, and anxiety.\nStudents should be pushed toward a nuanced debate: clear succession can stabilize the future, while ambiguous succession can preserve current authority. Both choices have risks.",
          "studentExplanation": "Elizabeth I delayed naming a successor because succession is not just a legal detail; it changes where people place their loyalty. If everyone knows who comes next, the future leader can start shaping the present before the old reign is over. But if no one knows, the current leader may preserve authority while creating uncertainty, rivalry, and fear about what happens after the end.\n\nElizabeth I’s succession strategy shows uncertainty as a political tool. Naming an heir can stabilize a future transition, but it can also create a rival center of loyalty in the present, so not knowing who is next can help a ruler remain the only focus. Use this to track how endings begin before they officially happen: what is ending, who notices it first, what signs make it feel near, and why people act differently in the near-end zone.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows that transitions can begin in people’s minds before they happen officially. At the section level, it deepens The End Is Nearish by asking when an ending truly starts: at death, departure, announcement, or rumor. At the year-theme level, it connects to thresholds and prediction because the future can pull power away from the present.",
