          "title": "Profiting from Disaster",
          "guidingSection": "The End is Nearish",
          "rawOfficialText": "Some investors are looking for business opportunities around the warming of the Earth. Explore some of those opportunities, then discuss with your team: should people be allowed to profit from rising temperatures? Could you imagine a company (or even a government) intentionally contributing to climate change, or other potential disasters, to benefit its own interests?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Business opportunities around warming — Politico",
              "url": "https://www.politico.com/news/2025/12/26/betting-on-climate-failure-investors-could-earn-billions-00677281"
            },
            {
              "label": "E&E News version of Politico article",
              "url": "https://www.eenews.net/articles/betting-on-climate-failure-these-investors-could-earn-billions/"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The Politico/E&E link should be treated as the core text of the entry. It is not just about “people making money from climate change” in a vague way; it specifically reports investment in solar geoengineering and planet-cooling technologies with uncertain side effects and weak regulation.\nThe article creates a subtle ethical distinction: investors may not want catastrophe, but they may profit if governments and societies decide warming has become bad enough to justify risky climate intervention. That is different from ordinary climate adaptation, because the business case may grow stronger as prevention fails.\nStudents should not be pushed to think every disaster-related business is evil. The important debate is incentive design: preparation can reduce harm, while profit models can sometimes normalize, exploit, or deepen the conditions they claim to solve.",
          "studentExplanation": "Profiting from disaster is not as simple as saying all crisis businesses are bad. People need tools, shelters, insurance, adaptation systems, and climate technologies. But the Politico/E&E link raises a sharper problem: if investors can make billions from risky climate interventions such as solar geoengineering, their financial success may depend on climate failure becoming bad enough to create demand. The ethical question is whether preparation reduces harm or quietly creates incentives to accept disaster.\n\nSolar geoengineering and climate-risk investing make the ethical problem sharper. Preparing for harm is not the same as wanting harm, but if a business grows more valuable as disaster worsens, students should ask who controls the tool and who carries the risk. Use this to track how endings begin before they officially happen: what is ending, who notices it first, what signs make it feel near, and why people act differently in the near-end zone.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students distinguish useful preparation from harmful incentives. At the section level, it gives The End Is Nearish a contemporary economic ending: apocalypse becomes a market opportunity. At the year-theme level, it connects to the future and prediction because some systems may begin planning not to prevent collapse, but to profit from living with it.",
          "takeaway": "Useful response and harmful incentive can overlap",
