          "sectionId": "the-lovely-and-the-liminal",
          "title": "The Architecture of Waiting",
          "guidingSection": "The Lovely and the Liminal",
          "rawOfficialText": "If you’ve ever gone to the doctor, the odds are good you’ve sat in a room waiting for someone to call your name. With your team, explore the architecture of waiting. How can a waiting room decrease anxiety (or amplify it)? How would you design waiting rooms differently for different purposes?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Architecture of waiting / non-places - ArtReview",
              "url": "https://artreview.com/just-passing-through-the-history-of-societys-non-places/"
            },
            {
              "label": "The psychology of waiting rooms - Medium",
              "url": "https://medium.com/@oliviaturne442/the-psychology-of-waiting-rooms-how-design-influences-anxiety-5660fee79657"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "The ArtReview article is especially important. It introduces antespace: rooms you enter on the way to other rooms, where mobility and immobility converge. It also shows that waiting is social and political: layouts, doors, appointment screens, and access rules organize behavior.\nThe waiting-room psychology link brings the concept down to student-level design choices: light, color, furniture, noise, privacy, personal space, and uncertainty can reduce or intensify anxiety. Together the links show that waiting rooms are not neutral containers; they are designed emotional thresholds.",
          "studentExplanation": "Waiting rooms are designed thresholds. They hold people between one stage and the next: before a doctor, interview, office, flight, or decision. The links show two important ideas. First, waiting spaces have a history and can organize social behavior. Second, design choices such as light, color, seating, noise, privacy, and information can change anxiety. A waiting room is therefore not just a room with chairs; it is architecture that shapes how waiting feels.\n\nThe architecture notes add history: antechambers, waiting rooms, atriums, queues, and angled seating can choreograph patience, status, silence, and anxiety. A waiting room is therefore not neutral; it organizes people while they are between one authority and the next. Use this to test the word “liminal” carefully: what threshold is present, where movement pauses, how the space changes memory or feeling, and whether the in-between is useful, beautiful, scary, or too vague.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students notice that waiting is shaped by space. At the section level, it connects liminality to everyday design rather than only art or horror. At the year-theme level, it connects to waiting because the journey can feel very different depending on how the in-between is designed.",
          "takeaway": "Design can shape how uncertainty is felt.",
