          "sectionId": "the-lovely-and-the-liminal",
          "title": "Stuck in the In-Between",
          "guidingSection": "The Lovely and the Liminal",
          "rawOfficialText": "To be in-between is to pass through a space where the normal rules of movement, time, and social interaction are suspended—but only briefly, on the way to elsewhere. But what happens if you’re stuck in such a place? As you explore the selections below, consider: how should we approach spending time in liminal spaces? Should we do more to seek them out?\n\nSamuel Beckett | Waiting for Godot, Scene 2 (1953)\n\nPablo Neruda | “Keeping Still” (1958)\n\nPhilippe Orreindy | I'll Wait for the Next One... (2002)\n\nMarcel Ayme | “The Man Who Could Walk through Walls” (1941)\n\nAmor Towles | A Gentleman in Moscow (Excerpt) (2019)",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Waiting for Godot PDF",
              "url": "https://www.lsgalilei.org/images/FilesGalilei/Docenti/Dipartimenti/Lingue/WaitingForGodotGB.pdf"
            },
            {
              "label": "Keeping Still PDF",
              "url": "https://www.mcgill.ca/poetrymatters/files/poetrymatters/neruda_-_keeping_still.pdf"
            },
            {
              "label": "The Man Who Could Walk through Walls",
              "url": "https://shortstoryproject.com/stories/the-man-who-could-walk-through-walls/"
            },
            {
              "label": "A Gentleman in Moscow excerpt",
              "url": "https://www.cbsnews.com/news/book-excerpt-a-gentleman-in-moscow-by-amor-towles/"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "Waiting for Godot is the anchor: the linked PDF shows a setting reduced to a country road, a tree, evening, and repeated waiting. The famous “We’re waiting for Godot” dynamic makes delay the structure of life, not just a plot point.\nNeruda’s “Keeping Still” changes stuckness into chosen stillness: pausing can become reflection rather than failure. Orreindy’s short film literalizes urban waiting and missed human connection. Aymé’s wall-walker and Towles’s hotel-bound count both explore confinement: unusual freedom or elegance can still become a form of being stuck.",
          "studentExplanation": "This entry asks what happens when liminality stops being brief. In Waiting for Godot, waiting becomes a whole existence. In Neruda’s “Keeping Still,” stopping can become a conscious pause. In I’ll Wait for the Next One..., waiting happens in a public transit space but becomes emotional. In The Man Who Could Walk through Walls and A Gentleman in Moscow, unusual spaces and limits reshape identity. The in-between is no longer just a passage; it becomes a condition.\n\nThe sources show liminality becoming a life condition. Godot never arrives, Neruda asks for a pause from constant doing, the subway short film turns waiting into disappointment, Dutilleul gets trapped in the wall, and Rostov lives between punishment and refuge inside a hotel. Use this to test the word “liminal” carefully: what threshold is present, where movement pauses, how the space changes memory or feeling, and whether the in-between is useful, beautiful, scary, or too vague.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this deepens liminality into time, waiting, and confinement. At the section level, it connects literature, film, and fiction around suspended life. At the year-theme level, it asks whether being “not there yet” can become meaningful, painful, or even chosen.",
          "takeaway": "A passage can become a way of living.",
