          "sectionId": "the-lovely-and-the-liminal",
          "title": "Music for Airports?",
          "guidingSection": "The Lovely and the Liminal",
          "rawOfficialText": "Some people put on a little music when they’re talking with someone else, or when they’re eating dinner—just to fill the room with a certain kind of background sound. Ambient music is designed to do exactly that, without needing you to focus on it—and it’s a newer genre than you might think. Consider the examples below, beginning with composer Brian Eno’s effort to make airports less stressful, and then discuss with your team: should we be playing more ambient music and fewer pop songs, podcasts, and YouTube videos when the goal is just to keep away the quiet? Or is ambient music best reserved for liminal spaces—is it, in fact, music for airports?\n\nBrian Eno | Ambient 1: Music for Airports (1979)\n\nHiroshi Yoshimura | Music for Nine Postcards (1982)\n\nMax Richter | Sleep (2015)",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Hiroshi Yoshimura - Music for Nine Postcards",
              "url": "https://youtu.be/Qj1Q-0d1WZo"
            },
            {
              "label": "Max Richter - Sleep",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CWYA99Zb13Y"
            }
          ],
          "deepLinkAnalysis": "Music for Airports is central because it was designed for a liminal environment: an airport terminal where people are waiting, anxious, and between destinations. Eno’s ambient idea is that music can be interesting if noticed but ignorable if not, shaping a space without demanding focus.\nYoshimura and Richter expand the idea. Music for Nine Postcards creates a quiet environment for looking, waiting, and dwelling; Sleep turns music into an extended threshold between waking and sleeping. Together the examples show liminality as sound: atmosphere, not narrative.",
          "studentExplanation": "Ambient music is designed to shape a space without demanding full attention. Brian Eno’s Music for Airports is the key example because it was made for a liminal place: an airport, where people wait, move, worry, and pass through. Hiroshi Yoshimura’s Music for Nine Postcards and Max Richter’s Sleep show that ambient music can also support looking, resting, drifting, or crossing between waking and sleep. This entry turns liminality into sound.\n\nAmbient music should be explained as design for attention. Eno wanted music that could be ignored and still reward listening, and the airport matters because travelers there are anxious, suspended, and between places; Yoshimura and Richter broaden the idea into looking, resting, and sleeping. Use this to test the word “liminal” carefully: what threshold is present, where movement pauses, how the space changes memory or feeling, and whether the in-between is useful, beautiful, scary, or too vague.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand music as atmosphere rather than performance. At the section level, it closes The Lovely and the Liminal by showing that liminal spaces can be designed through sound. At the year-theme level, it connects to waiting because sound can change how “not there yet” feels.",
          "takeaway": "Sound can design how transition feels.",
