          "studentExplanation": "Even the most famous artworks usually have a process behind them. Artists test, repeat, revise, copy, simplify, intensify, and sometimes return to the same idea more than once. The Mona Lisa comparison, Van Gogh’s Bedroom versions, Munch’s movement from Despair to The Scream, and Matisse’s Dance I and Dance II show different kinds of artistic development. Some changes are visual, some are emotional, and some are even scientific discoveries made later through letters and paint analysis. The important point is that a finished artwork often hides a long in-between phase of versions, studies, experiments, and decisions.\n\nThe extra notes make each art case concrete: the Isleworth Mona Lisa raises questions of version and attribution, Van Gogh’s Bedrooms differ in scale and purpose, Munch intensifies Despair into The Scream, and Matisse’s Dance changes color, detail, and force between versions. Use this to make process visible: what changed between versions, where the earlier form still survives, how revision altered meaning, and why a “finished” work often hides many unfinished stages.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students see that artistic masterpieces are not usually one-shot miracles. At the section level, it opens There’s a Draft in Here by making the creative process visible through exact works students can compare. At the year-theme level, it connects to drafts, progress, and planning because “getting there” in art often means passing through versions that look almost there, not there yet, or differently there.",
          "takeaway": "Revision can change the meaning of a work, not only its polish",
