          "sectionId": "were-all-in-this-to-get-there",
          "title": "What a Gantt Chart Shows - and What It Hides",
          "guidingSection": "We're All in This to Get There",
          "rawOfficialText": "The makers of the pyramids might have benefitted from a Gantt chart - an approach invented in the early 20th century which shows a project schedule in the form of a bar chart. Some bars represent tasks that can be worked on at the same time; others need earlier bars to be completed before you can start on them. Explore how Gantt Charts helped in the construction of the Hoover Dam in the United States and how they even became popular in the early Soviet Union, then discuss with your team: what is gained when you translate a project into this kind of format - and what is lost?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Gantt chart - Forbes",
              "url": "https://www.forbes.com/advisor/business/software/what-is-a-gantt-chart/"
            },
            {
              "label": "History of the Gantt chart",
              "url": "https://ganttchart.com/history_of_the_gantt_chart/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "A Gantt chart turns a project into tasks stretched across time. It can show what starts when, what overlaps, and what must wait for an earlier task to finish. That visibility is powerful: it helps teams coordinate complicated work, like the Hoover Dam. But it also has a limit. A neat bar schedule can make messy reality look more controlled than it really is. Weather, materials, workers, design changes, politics, and accidents do not always fit cleanly into bars.\n\nA Gantt chart shows tasks on a timeline, overlaps, assignments, dependencies, baselines, and visible progress. It hides difficulty, morale, weather, politics, rework, and whether a neat schedule has become more important than the real project. Use this to connect ambition to coordination: what the project is trying to finish, where time and resources break down, how tools make work visible, and why people remain the hardest part of planning.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows why Gantt charts became influential: they make project time visible. At the section level, it introduces one of the classic tools for making progress legible. At the year-theme level, it connects to planning and delay because seeing a path does not guarantee that the project will follow it.",
          "takeaway": "A schedule can make work visible without fully controlling reality",
          "subjects": [
            "Economics & Trade"
          ],
          "bigIdeas": [
            "Infrastructure Shapes Behavior",
            "Visible vs Real",
            "Performed Progress",
            "Managing Uncertainty"
          ],
