          "sectionId": "were-all-in-this-to-get-there",
          "title": "The Laws of Human Effort",
          "guidingSection": "We're All in This to Get There",
          "rawOfficialText": "Managers need people to manage - but those people can be frustratingly slow and easily distracted. Explore the psychological and structural laws that supposedly govern human effort, then discuss with your team: how do they apply to your preparations for this competition?\n\nThe Hawthorne Effect | Hofstadter’s Law | the 90-90 Rule | Conway’s Law\nPutt’s Law | Illich’s Law | Laborit’s Law | Brooks’ Law",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "The Hawthorne Effect in 3 minutes",
              "url": "https://youtu.be/o4XX90lqT6E?si=PPJZsy6YLzVTLdYm"
            },
            {
              "label": "90-90 Rule video",
              "url": "https://youtu.be/BEGStDKSVuU?si=YX9sCbomp_y6ygHX"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Plans do not fail only because tools are bad. They also fail because people are people. The Hawthorne Effect suggests observation changes behavior. Hofstadter’s Law warns that work takes longer than expected. The 90-90 Rule jokes that the final part of a project can consume far more time than planned. Conway’s Law says systems often reflect the teams that build them. Brooks’ Law warns that adding people to a late project can make it later. Together, these ideas show that progress depends on psychology, incentives, communication, attention, and structure - not just effort.\n\nThese “laws” are warnings against treating humans as simple inputs. Observation changes behavior, estimates slip, the last part expands, teams mirror communication structures, managers may misunderstand technology, and adding people can create more coordination work than progress. Use this to connect ambition to coordination: what the project is trying to finish, where time and resources break down, how tools make work visible, and why people remain the hardest part of planning.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students understand why teamwork and effort behave unpredictably. At the section level, it explains why project management cannot be only charts and tools. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress because getting there together means managing human attention, coordination, and limits.",
          "takeaway": "Productivity is shaped by attention, structure, pressure, and coordination",
