          "sectionId": "where-the-sidewalk-starts",
          "title": "Why Moving Sidewalks Never Took Over the World",
          "guidingSection": "Where the Sidewalk Starts",
          "rawOfficialText": "In the once-futuristic world of the Jetsons, the sidewalks don’t just sit there: they whisk people along to their destinations. Something like this still happens at many airports and even some amusement parks. Learn more about historical efforts to popularize moving sidewalks. Discuss with your team: why didn’t they catch on more widely? Where would you install them today, if you could?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Historical efforts - Smithsonian",
              "url": "https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/moving-sidewalks-before-the-jetsons-17484942/"
            },
            {
              "label": "First moving walkway - Guinness",
              "url": "https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/106892-first-moving-walkway"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Moving sidewalks feel like a perfect future: instead of walking, people glide toward their destination. But the idea is much older than The Jetsons. Nineteenth- and twentieth-century inventors imagined movable pavement for fairs, cities, stadiums, and subway systems. The 1893 Chicago World’s Columbian Exposition even had an early moving sidewalk on a pier. The reason the idea never took over ordinary streets is not that it was fake. It is that it worked best in special, controlled environments, such as airports, amusement parks, and exhibitions, where movement is predictable and maintenance is worth the cost.\n\nMoving sidewalks failed as ordinary urban infrastructure because they need controlled flow, maintenance, predictable entry and exit points, and enough demand to justify cost. That is why they survive better in airports, exhibitions, and amusement parks than on every city street. Use this to read infrastructure as a design choice: what space is being created, where pedestrians or cars are placed, how movement changes, and who gains or loses from that layout.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students distinguish a niche success from a universal transformation. At the section level, it shows that futuristic infrastructure survives only when it matches real-world conditions. At the year-theme level, it connects to progress and prediction because not every “almost obvious” invention becomes everyday life.",
          "takeaway": "Progress depends on fit between technology, place, cost, and human behavior",
