          "sectionId": "where-were-going-well-still-need-them",
          "title": "Can a Bus Journey Be a Road Trip?",
          "guidingSection": "Where We're Going, We'll Still Need Them",
          "rawOfficialText": "Be sure to look into other long distance overland journeys, including the once-legendary London to Calcutta bus service and the still operational Transoceánica from Brazil to Peru. Can they be called road trips even if they don’t take place in cars? Or is it only a road trip if you can choose when and where to stop along the way?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "London to Calcutta bus service",
              "url": "https://secretldn.com/longest-bus-route-in-the-world-london-to-calcutta/"
            },
            {
              "label": "Transoceánica route",
              "url": "https://www.riotimesonline.com/brazil-news/rio-travel/the-worlds-longest-bus-route-leaves-brazil-and-lasts-5-days-its-surreal/"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Long overland bus journeys show that road travel does not belong only to private cars. A bus from London to Calcutta or a route across South America can be epic, exhausting, and transformative. But they also raise a question: is a road trip about distance and landscape, or about the freedom to choose when to stop, where to turn, and how to shape the journey?\n\nLong bus journeys test whether a road trip requires private control. London-to-Calcutta style routes or South American overland buses create distance, landscape, discomfort, and shared experience, but less freedom to stop or detour, so agency becomes the key variable. Use this to treat roads as systems, not background: what the route is built to do, where it channels people or goods, how it changes choices, and why routes remain cultural even after their practical role changes.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students test the limits of a familiar term. At the section level, it complicates the road-trip myth by adding collective, scheduled, and non-car overland travel. At the year-theme level, it connects to journeys because freedom, not distance alone, may shape how travel feels.",
          "takeaway": "A road trip may depend on agency and experience as much as on distance or vehicle",
