          "sectionId": "where-were-going-well-still-need-them",
          "title": "Motels: Sleeping on the Road",
          "guidingSection": "Where We're Going, We'll Still Need Them",
          "rawOfficialText": "People on road trips needed a place to sleep at night. Early on, many simply pulled off the road and camped beside their cars; over time, a new kind of car-friendly hotel emerged to serve them. Read about the world’s first motel and the history of motels since, then consider: are there equivalents in your country—and have you ever stayed at one?",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "First motel history",
              "url": "https://www.pbssocal.org/shows/artbound/swimming-pools-and-movie-stars-a-history-of-the-worlds-first-motel"
            },
            {
              "label": "Motel history",
              "url": "https://sah-archipedia.org/essays/CA-01-ART-01"
            },
            {
              "label": "Britannica motel overview",
              "url": "https://www.britannica.com/technology/motel"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "When cars made long-distance road travel more common, travelers needed places to sleep without leaving the road world behind. The motel emerged as a motor hotel: a car-friendly form of lodging designed for easy access, parking, short stays, and continued movement. It is not simply a smaller hotel; it is architecture shaped by road culture.\n\nThe motel is architecture shaped by the car: parking near the room, easy highway access, short stays, and a promise that sleep is only a pause before more movement. It is not just a cheap hotel; it is lodging designed around road rhythm. Use this to treat roads as systems, not background: what the route is built to do, where it channels people or goods, how it changes choices, and why routes remain cultural even after their practical role changes.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this shows how movement creates new building types. At the section level, it extends road culture from driving to stopping. At the year-theme level, it connects to home and wandering because motels are classic in-between spaces: places to pause without fully arriving.",
          "takeaway": "New movement patterns create new architecture for people between home and destination",
          "subjects": [
            "Design / Architecture / Urbanism",
            "History"
          ],
