          "sectionId": "where-were-going-well-still-need-them",
          "title": "Songs, Paintings, and the Feeling of the Highway",
          "guidingSection": "Where We're Going, We'll Still Need Them",
          "rawOfficialText": "Consider the art and music selections below: what aspects of being on the road do they reflect? Do they over-idealize the experience of traveling by car—or critique it unfairly?\n\nNat Cole | “Get Your Kicks on Route 66” (1946)\nEdward Hopper | Western Motel (1957)\nEdward Ruscha | Standard Station (1966)\nWillie Nelson | “On the Road Again Song” (1980)\nDavid Hockney | Pearblossom Highway (1985)\nTom Cochrane | “Life is a Highway” (1991)\nBic Runga | “Drive” (1996)\nNorah Jones | “Come Away with Me” (2002)",
          "links": [
            {
              "label": "Edward Hopper",
              "url": "https://www.edwardhopper.net/western-motel.jsp"
            },
            {
              "label": "Edward Ruscha",
              "url": "https://www.moma.org/collection/works/76637"
            },
            {
              "label": "Willie Nelson",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dBN86y30Ufc"
            },
            {
              "label": "David Hockney",
              "url": "https://davidhockneyexhibition.weebly.com/artwork-critiques.html"
            },
            {
              "label": "Tom Cochrane",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U3sMjm9Eloo"
            },
            {
              "label": "Bic Runga",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xHGUh30U4tQ"
            },
            {
              "label": "Norah Jones",
              "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lbjZPFBD6JU"
            }
          ],
          "studentExplanation": "Road songs and road images can make travel feel exciting, lonely, glamorous, repetitive, free, fake, or intimate. Some works celebrate the highway, while others quietly reveal its stillness, sameness, or artificial charm. This entry asks whether road culture is being romanticized, criticized, or both at once.\n\nThe cultural works make highways emotional objects. Route 66 songs sell freedom and rhythm, Hopper makes roadside stillness lonely, Ruscha turns gas stations into clean icons, and road images can celebrate mobility while also showing sameness or isolation. Use this to treat roads as systems, not background: what the route is built to do, where it channels people or goods, how it changes choices, and why routes remain cultural even after their practical role changes.",
          "whyItMatters": "At the entry level, this helps students compare how music and visual art translate travel into mood. At the section level, it adds emotional depth to the road-trip cluster. At the year-theme level, it connects to home and wandering because being on the road can feel like escape, performance, loneliness, or desire all at once.",
          "takeaway": "Art can both celebrate and question the road as freedom, routine, loneliness, or fantasy",
